8 /// ----
9 /// \file ----
10 /// This file implements a CFG stacking pass. ----
11 /// ----
12 /// This pass inserts BLOCK, LOOP, and TRY markers to mark the start of scopes, ----
13 /// since scope boundaries serve as the labels for WebAssembly's control ----
14 /// transfers. ----
15 /// ----
16 /// This is sufficient to convert arbitrary CFGs into a form that works on ----
17 /// WebAssembly, provided that all loops are single-entry. ----
18 /// ----
19 /// In case we use exceptions, this pass also fixes mismatches in unwind ----
20 /// destinations created during transforming CFG into wasm structured format. ----
21 /// ----
22 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
23 ----

59 // For each block whose label represents the end of a scope, record the block ----
60 // which holds the beginning of the scope. This will allow us to quickly skip ----
61 // over scoped regions when walking blocks. ----

64 int EndNo = End->getNumber(); 0
65 if (!ScopeTops[EndNo] || ScopeTops[EndNo]->getNumber() > Begin->getNumber()) 0
66 ScopeTops[EndNo] = Begin; 0
67 } 0

158 /// Test whether Pred has any terminators explicitly branching to MBB, as ----
159 /// opposed to falling through. Note that it's possible (eg. in unoptimized ----
160 /// code) for a branch instruction to both branch to a block and fallthrough ----
161 /// to it, so we check the actual branch operands to see if there are any ----
162 /// explicit mentions. ----
163 static bool explicitlyBranchesTo(MachineBasicBlock *Pred, 0
164 MachineBasicBlock *MBB) { ----
165 for (MachineInstr &MI : Pred->terminators()) 0
166 for (MachineOperand &MO : MI.explicit_operands()) 0
167 if (MO.isMBB() && MO.getMBB() == MBB) 0
168 return true; 0
169 return false; 0
170 } ----
171 ----
172 // Returns an iterator to the earliest position possible within the MBB, ----
173 // satisfying the restrictions given by BeforeSet and AfterSet. BeforeSet ----
174 // contains instructions that should go before the marker, and AfterSet contains ----
175 // ones that should go after the marker. In this function, AfterSet is only ----
176 // used for validation checking. ----
177 template ----
178 static MachineBasicBlock::iterator ----
179 getEarliestInsertPos(MachineBasicBlock *MBB, const Container &BeforeSet, 0
180 const Container &AfterSet) { ----
181 auto InsertPos = MBB->end(); 0
182 while (InsertPos != MBB->begin()) { 0
183 if (BeforeSet.count(&*std::prev(InsertPos))) { 0
184 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
185 // Validation check ----
186 for (auto Pos = InsertPos, E = MBB->begin(); Pos != E; --Pos) 0
187 assert(!AfterSet.count(&*std::prev(Pos))); 0
188 #endif ----
189 break; 0
190 } ----
191 --InsertPos; 0
192 } ----
193 return InsertPos; 0
194 } ----
195 ----
196 // Returns an iterator to the latest position possible within the MBB, ----
197 // satisfying the restrictions given by BeforeSet and AfterSet. BeforeSet ----
198 // contains instructions that should go before the marker, and AfterSet contains ----
199 // ones that should go after the marker. In this function, BeforeSet is only ----
200 // used for validation checking. ----
201 template ----
202 static MachineBasicBlock::iterator ----
203 getLatestInsertPos(MachineBasicBlock *MBB, const Container &BeforeSet, 0
204 const Container &AfterSet) { ----
205 auto InsertPos = MBB->begin(); 0
206 while (InsertPos != MBB->end()) { 0
207 if (AfterSet.count(&*InsertPos)) { 0
208 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
209 // Validation check ----
210 for (auto Pos = InsertPos, E = MBB->end(); Pos != E; ++Pos) 0
211 assert(!BeforeSet.count(&*Pos)); 0
212 #endif ----
213 break; 0
214 } ----
215 ++InsertPos; 0
216 } ----
217 return InsertPos; 0
218 } ----

235 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::unregisterScope(MachineInstr *Begin) { 0
236 assert(BeginToEnd.count(Begin)); 0
237 MachineInstr *End = BeginToEnd[Begin]; 0
238 assert(EndToBegin.count(End)); 0
239 BeginToEnd.erase(Begin); 0
240 EndToBegin.erase(End); 0
241 MachineBasicBlock *EHPad = TryToEHPad.lookup(Begin); 0
242 if (EHPad) { 0
243 assert(EHPadToTry.count(EHPad)); 0
244 TryToEHPad.erase(Begin); 0
245 EHPadToTry.erase(EHPad); 0
246 } ----
247 } 0

249 /// Insert a BLOCK marker for branches to MBB (if needed). ----
250 // TODO Consider a more generalized way of handling block (and also loop and ----
251 // try) signatures when we implement the multi-value proposal later. ----
252 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::placeBlockMarker(MachineBasicBlock &MBB) { 0
253 assert(!MBB.isEHPad()); 0
254 MachineFunction &MF = *MBB.getParent(); 0
255 auto &MDT = getAnalysis(); 0
256 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
257 const auto &MFI = *MF.getInfo(); 0
258 ----
259 // First compute the nearest common dominator of all forward non-fallthrough ----
260 // predecessors so that we minimize the time that the BLOCK is on the stack, ----
261 // which reduces overall stack height. ----
262 MachineBasicBlock *Header = nullptr; 0
263 bool IsBranchedTo = false; 0
264 int MBBNumber = MBB.getNumber(); 0
265 for (MachineBasicBlock *Pred : MBB.predecessors()) { 0
266 if (Pred->getNumber() < MBBNumber) { 0
267 Header = Header ? MDT.findNearestCommonDominator(Header, Pred) : Pred; 0
268 if (explicitlyBranchesTo(Pred, &MBB)) 0
269 IsBranchedTo = true; 0
270 } ----
271 } ----
272 if (!Header) 0
273 return; 0
274 if (!IsBranchedTo) 0
275 return; 0
276 ----
277 assert(&MBB != &MF.front() && "Header blocks shouldn't have predecessors"); 0
278 MachineBasicBlock *LayoutPred = MBB.getPrevNode(); 0
279 ----
280 // If the nearest common dominator is inside a more deeply nested context, ----
281 // walk out to the nearest scope which isn't more deeply nested. ----
282 for (MachineFunction::iterator I(LayoutPred), E(Header); I != E; --I) { 0
283 if (MachineBasicBlock *ScopeTop = ScopeTops[I->getNumber()]) { 0
284 if (ScopeTop->getNumber() > Header->getNumber()) { 0
285 // Skip over an intervening scope. ----
286 I = std::next(ScopeTop->getIterator()); 0
287 } else { ----
288 // We found a scope level at an appropriate depth. ----
289 Header = ScopeTop; 0
290 break; 0
291 } ----
292 } ----
293 } ----
294 ----
295 // Decide where in Header to put the BLOCK. ----
296 ----
297 // Instructions that should go before the BLOCK. ----
298 SmallPtrSet BeforeSet; 0
299 // Instructions that should go after the BLOCK. ----
300 SmallPtrSet AfterSet; 0
301 for (const auto &MI : *Header) { 0
302 // If there is a previously placed LOOP marker and the bottom block of the ----
303 // loop is above MBB, it should be after the BLOCK, because the loop is ----
304 // nested in this BLOCK. Otherwise it should be before the BLOCK. ----
305 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::LOOP) { 0
306 auto *LoopBottom = BeginToEnd[&MI]->getParent()->getPrevNode(); 0
307 if (MBB.getNumber() > LoopBottom->getNumber()) 0
308 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
309 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
310 else ----
311 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
312 #endif ----
313 } ----
314 ----
315 // If there is a previously placed BLOCK/TRY marker and its corresponding ----
316 // END marker is before the current BLOCK's END marker, that should be ----
317 // placed after this BLOCK. Otherwise it should be placed before this BLOCK ----
318 // marker. ----
319 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::BLOCK || 0
320 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::TRY) { 0
321 if (BeginToEnd[&MI]->getParent()->getNumber() <= MBB.getNumber()) 0
322 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
323 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
324 else ----
325 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
326 #endif ----
327 } ----
328 ----
329 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
330 // All END_(BLOCK|LOOP|TRY) markers should be before the BLOCK. ----
331 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_BLOCK || 0
332 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_LOOP || 0
333 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_TRY) 0
334 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
335 #endif ----
336 ----
337 // Terminators should go after the BLOCK. ----
338 if (MI.isTerminator()) 0
339 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
340 } ----
341 ----
342 // Local expression tree should go after the BLOCK. ----
343 for (auto I = Header->getFirstTerminator(), E = Header->begin(); I != E; 0
344 --I) { 0
345 if (std::prev(I)->isDebugInstr() || std::prev(I)->isPosition()) 0
346 continue; 0
347 if (WebAssembly::isChild(*std::prev(I), MFI)) 0
348 AfterSet.insert(&*std::prev(I)); 0
349 else ----
350 break; 0
351 } ----
352 ----
353 // Add the BLOCK. ----
354 WebAssembly::BlockType ReturnType = WebAssembly::BlockType::Void; 0
355 auto InsertPos = getLatestInsertPos(Header, BeforeSet, AfterSet); 0
356 MachineInstr *Begin = ----
357 BuildMI(*Header, InsertPos, Header->findDebugLoc(InsertPos), 0
358 TII.get(WebAssembly::BLOCK)) ----
359 .addImm(int64_t(ReturnType)); 0
360 ----
361 // Decide where in Header to put the END_BLOCK. ----
362 BeforeSet.clear(); 0
363 AfterSet.clear(); 0
364 for (auto &MI : MBB) { 0
365 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
366 // END_BLOCK should precede existing LOOP and TRY markers. ----
367 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::LOOP || 0
368 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::TRY) 0
369 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
370 #endif ----
371 ----
372 // If there is a previously placed END_LOOP marker and the header of the ----
373 // loop is above this block's header, the END_LOOP should be placed after ----
374 // the BLOCK, because the loop contains this block. Otherwise the END_LOOP ----
375 // should be placed before the BLOCK. The same for END_TRY. ----
376 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_LOOP || 0
377 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_TRY) { 0
378 if (EndToBegin[&MI]->getParent()->getNumber() >= Header->getNumber()) 0
379 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
380 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
381 else ----
382 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
383 #endif ----
384 } ----
385 } ----
386 ----
387 // Mark the end of the block. ----
388 InsertPos = getEarliestInsertPos(&MBB, BeforeSet, AfterSet); 0
389 MachineInstr *End = BuildMI(MBB, InsertPos, MBB.findPrevDebugLoc(InsertPos), 0
390 TII.get(WebAssembly::END_BLOCK)); 0
391 registerScope(Begin, End); 0
392 ----
393 // Track the farthest-spanning scope that ends at this point. ----
394 updateScopeTops(Header, &MBB); 0
395 } 0

397 /// Insert a LOOP marker for a loop starting at MBB (if it's a loop header). ----
398 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::placeLoopMarker(MachineBasicBlock &MBB) { 0
399 MachineFunction &MF = *MBB.getParent(); 0
400 const auto &MLI = getAnalysis(); 0
401 const auto &WEI = getAnalysis(); 0
402 SortRegionInfo SRI(MLI, WEI); 0
403 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
404 ----
405 MachineLoop *Loop = MLI.getLoopFor(&MBB); 0
406 if (!Loop || Loop->getHeader() != &MBB) 0
407 return; 0
408 ----
409 // The operand of a LOOP is the first block after the loop. If the loop is the ----
410 // bottom of the function, insert a dummy block at the end. ----
411 MachineBasicBlock *Bottom = SRI.getBottom(Loop); 0
412 auto Iter = std::next(Bottom->getIterator()); 0
413 if (Iter == MF.end()) { 0
414 getAppendixBlock(MF); 0
415 Iter = std::next(Bottom->getIterator()); 0
416 } ----
417 MachineBasicBlock *AfterLoop = &*Iter; 0
418 ----
419 // Decide where in Header to put the LOOP. ----
420 SmallPtrSet BeforeSet; 0
421 SmallPtrSet AfterSet; 0
422 for (const auto &MI : MBB) { 0
423 // LOOP marker should be after any existing loop that ends here. Otherwise ----
424 // we assume the instruction belongs to the loop. ----
425 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_LOOP) 0
426 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
427 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
428 else ----
429 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
430 #endif ----
431 } ----
432 ----
433 // Mark the beginning of the loop. ----
434 auto InsertPos = getEarliestInsertPos(&MBB, BeforeSet, AfterSet); 0
435 MachineInstr *Begin = BuildMI(MBB, InsertPos, MBB.findDebugLoc(InsertPos), 0
436 TII.get(WebAssembly::LOOP)) ----
437 .addImm(int64_t(WebAssembly::BlockType::Void)); 0
438 ----
439 // Decide where in Header to put the END_LOOP. ----
440 BeforeSet.clear(); 0
441 AfterSet.clear(); 0
442 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
443 for (const auto &MI : MBB) 0
444 // Existing END_LOOP markers belong to parent loops of this loop ----
445 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_LOOP) 0
446 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
447 #endif ----
448 ----
449 // Mark the end of the loop (using arbitrary debug location that branched to ----
450 // the loop end as its location). ----
451 InsertPos = getEarliestInsertPos(AfterLoop, BeforeSet, AfterSet); 0
452 DebugLoc EndDL = AfterLoop->pred_empty() 0
453 ? DebugLoc() ----
454 : (*AfterLoop->pred_rbegin())->findBranchDebugLoc(); 0
455 MachineInstr *End = ----
456 BuildMI(*AfterLoop, InsertPos, EndDL, TII.get(WebAssembly::END_LOOP)); 0
457 registerScope(Begin, End); 0
458 ----
459 assert((!ScopeTops[AfterLoop->getNumber()] || 0
460 ScopeTops[AfterLoop->getNumber()]->getNumber() < MBB.getNumber()) && ----
461 "With block sorting the outermost loop for a block should be first."); ----
462 updateScopeTops(&MBB, AfterLoop); 0
463 } 0

465 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::placeTryMarker(MachineBasicBlock &MBB) { 0
466 assert(MBB.isEHPad()); 0
467 MachineFunction &MF = *MBB.getParent(); 0
468 auto &MDT = getAnalysis(); 0
469 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
470 const auto &MLI = getAnalysis(); 0
471 const auto &WEI = getAnalysis(); 0
472 SortRegionInfo SRI(MLI, WEI); 0
473 const auto &MFI = *MF.getInfo(); 0
474 ----
475 // Compute the nearest common dominator of all unwind predecessors ----
476 MachineBasicBlock *Header = nullptr; 0
477 int MBBNumber = MBB.getNumber(); 0
478 for (auto *Pred : MBB.predecessors()) { 0
479 if (Pred->getNumber() < MBBNumber) { 0
480 Header = Header ? MDT.findNearestCommonDominator(Header, Pred) : Pred; 0
481 assert(!explicitlyBranchesTo(Pred, &MBB) && 0
482 "Explicit branch to an EH pad!"); ----
483 } ----
484 } ----
485 if (!Header) 0
486 return; 0
487 ----
488 // If this try is at the bottom of the function, insert a dummy block at the ----
489 // end. ----
490 WebAssemblyException *WE = WEI.getExceptionFor(&MBB); 0
491 assert(WE); 0
492 MachineBasicBlock *Bottom = SRI.getBottom(WE); 0
493 ----
494 auto Iter = std::next(Bottom->getIterator()); 0
495 if (Iter == MF.end()) { 0
496 getAppendixBlock(MF); 0
497 Iter = std::next(Bottom->getIterator()); 0
498 } ----
499 MachineBasicBlock *Cont = &*Iter; 0
500 ----
501 assert(Cont != &MF.front()); 0
502 MachineBasicBlock *LayoutPred = Cont->getPrevNode(); 0
503 ----
504 // If the nearest common dominator is inside a more deeply nested context, ----
505 // walk out to the nearest scope which isn't more deeply nested. ----
506 for (MachineFunction::iterator I(LayoutPred), E(Header); I != E; --I) { 0
507 if (MachineBasicBlock *ScopeTop = ScopeTops[I->getNumber()]) { 0
508 if (ScopeTop->getNumber() > Header->getNumber()) { 0
509 // Skip over an intervening scope. ----
510 I = std::next(ScopeTop->getIterator()); 0
511 } else { ----
512 // We found a scope level at an appropriate depth. ----
513 Header = ScopeTop; 0
514 break; 0
515 } ----
516 } ----
517 } ----
518 ----
519 // Decide where in Header to put the TRY. ----
520 ----
521 // Instructions that should go before the TRY. ----
522 SmallPtrSet BeforeSet; 0
523 // Instructions that should go after the TRY. ----
524 SmallPtrSet AfterSet; 0
525 for (const auto &MI : *Header) { 0
526 // If there is a previously placed LOOP marker and the bottom block of the ----
527 // loop is above MBB, it should be after the TRY, because the loop is nested ----
528 // in this TRY. Otherwise it should be before the TRY. ----
529 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::LOOP) { 0
530 auto *LoopBottom = BeginToEnd[&MI]->getParent()->getPrevNode(); 0
531 if (MBB.getNumber() > LoopBottom->getNumber()) 0
532 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
533 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
534 else ----
535 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
536 #endif ----
537 } ----
538 ----
539 // All previously inserted BLOCK/TRY markers should be after the TRY because ----
540 // they are all nested trys. ----
541 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::BLOCK || 0
542 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::TRY) 0
543 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
544 ----
545 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
546 // All END_(BLOCK/LOOP/TRY) markers should be before the TRY. ----
547 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_BLOCK || 0
548 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_LOOP || 0
549 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_TRY) 0
550 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
551 #endif ----
552 ----
553 // Terminators should go after the TRY. ----
554 if (MI.isTerminator()) 0
555 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
556 } ----
557 ----
558 // If Header unwinds to MBB (= Header contains 'invoke'), the try block should ----
559 // contain the call within it. So the call should go after the TRY. The ----
560 // exception is when the header's terminator is a rethrow instruction, in ----
561 // which case that instruction, not a call instruction before it, is gonna ----
562 // throw. ----
563 MachineInstr *ThrowingCall = nullptr; 0
564 if (MBB.isPredecessor(Header)) { 0
565 auto TermPos = Header->getFirstTerminator(); 0
566 if (TermPos == Header->end() || 0
567 TermPos->getOpcode() != WebAssembly::RETHROW) { 0
568 for (auto &MI : reverse(*Header)) { 0
569 if (MI.isCall()) { 0
570 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
571 ThrowingCall = &MI; 0
572 // Possibly throwing calls are usually wrapped by EH_LABEL ----
573 // instructions. We don't want to split them and the call. ----
574 if (MI.getIterator() != Header->begin() && 0
575 std::prev(MI.getIterator())->isEHLabel()) { 0
576 AfterSet.insert(&*std::prev(MI.getIterator())); 0
577 ThrowingCall = &*std::prev(MI.getIterator()); 0
578 } ----
579 break; 0
580 } ----
581 } ----
582 } ----
583 } ----
584 ----
585 // Local expression tree should go after the TRY. ----
586 // For BLOCK placement, we start the search from the previous instruction of a ----
587 // BB's terminator, but in TRY's case, we should start from the previous ----
588 // instruction of a call that can throw, or a EH_LABEL that precedes the call, ----
589 // because the return values of the call's previous instructions can be ----
590 // stackified and consumed by the throwing call. ----
591 auto SearchStartPt = ThrowingCall ? MachineBasicBlock::iterator(ThrowingCall) ----
592 : Header->getFirstTerminator(); 0
593 for (auto I = SearchStartPt, E = Header->begin(); I != E; --I) { 0
594 if (std::prev(I)->isDebugInstr() || std::prev(I)->isPosition()) 0
595 continue; 0
596 if (WebAssembly::isChild(*std::prev(I), MFI)) 0
597 AfterSet.insert(&*std::prev(I)); 0
598 else ----
599 break; 0
600 } ----
601 ----
602 // Add the TRY. ----
603 auto InsertPos = getLatestInsertPos(Header, BeforeSet, AfterSet); 0
604 MachineInstr *Begin = ----
605 BuildMI(*Header, InsertPos, Header->findDebugLoc(InsertPos), 0
606 TII.get(WebAssembly::TRY)) ----
607 .addImm(int64_t(WebAssembly::BlockType::Void)); 0
608 ----
609 // Decide where in Header to put the END_TRY. ----
610 BeforeSet.clear(); 0
611 AfterSet.clear(); 0
612 for (const auto &MI : *Cont) { 0
613 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
614 // END_TRY should precede existing LOOP and BLOCK markers. ----
615 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::LOOP || 0
616 MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::BLOCK) 0
617 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
618 ----
619 // All END_TRY markers placed earlier belong to exceptions that contains ----
620 // this one. ----
621 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_TRY) 0
622 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
623 #endif ----
624 ----
625 // If there is a previously placed END_LOOP marker and its header is after ----
626 // where TRY marker is, this loop is contained within the 'catch' part, so ----
627 // the END_TRY marker should go after that. Otherwise, the whole try-catch ----
628 // is contained within this loop, so the END_TRY should go before that. ----
629 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_LOOP) { 0
630 // For a LOOP to be after TRY, LOOP's BB should be after TRY's BB; if they ----
631 // are in the same BB, LOOP is always before TRY. ----
632 if (EndToBegin[&MI]->getParent()->getNumber() > Header->getNumber()) 0
633 BeforeSet.insert(&MI); 0
634 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
635 else ----
636 AfterSet.insert(&MI); 0
637 #endif ----
638 } ----
639 ----
640 // It is not possible for an END_BLOCK to be already in this block. ----
641 } ----
642 ----
643 // Mark the end of the TRY. ----
644 InsertPos = getEarliestInsertPos(Cont, BeforeSet, AfterSet); 0
645 MachineInstr *End = ----
646 BuildMI(*Cont, InsertPos, Bottom->findBranchDebugLoc(), 0
647 TII.get(WebAssembly::END_TRY)); 0
648 registerTryScope(Begin, End, &MBB); 0
649 ----
650 // Track the farthest-spanning scope that ends at this point. We create two ----
651 // mappings: (BB with 'end_try' -> BB with 'try') and (BB with 'catch' -> BB ----
652 // with 'try'). We need to create 'catch' -> 'try' mapping here too because ----
653 // markers should not span across 'catch'. For example, this should not ----
654 // happen: ----
655 // ----
656 // try ----
657 // block --| (X) ----
658 // catch | ----
659 // end_block --| ----
660 // end_try ----
661 for (auto *End : {&MBB, Cont}) 0
662 updateScopeTops(Header, End); 0
663 } 0
664 ----
665 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::removeUnnecessaryInstrs(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
666 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
667 ----
668 // When there is an unconditional branch right before a catch instruction and ----
669 // it branches to the end of end_try marker, we don't need the branch, because ----
670 // it there is no exception, the control flow transfers to that point anyway. ----
671 // bb0: ----
672 // try ----
673 // ... ----
674 // br bb2 <- Not necessary ----
675 // bb1 (ehpad): ----
676 // catch ----
677 // ... ----
678 // bb2: <- Continuation BB ----
679 // end ----
680 // ----
681 // A more involved case: When the BB where 'end' is located is an another EH ----
682 // pad, the Cont (= continuation) BB is that EH pad's 'end' BB. For example, ----
683 // bb0: ----
684 // try ----
685 // try ----
686 // ... ----
687 // br bb3 <- Not necessary ----
688 // bb1 (ehpad): ----
689 // catch ----
690 // bb2 (ehpad): ----
691 // end ----
692 // catch ----
693 // ... ----
694 // bb3: <- Continuation BB ----
695 // end ----
696 // ----
697 // When the EH pad at hand is bb1, its matching end_try is in bb2. But it is ----
698 // another EH pad, so bb0's continuation BB becomes bb3. So 'br bb3' in the ----
699 // code can be deleted. This is why we run 'while' until 'Cont' is not an EH ----
700 // pad. ----
701 for (auto &MBB : MF) { 0
702 if (!MBB.isEHPad()) 0
703 continue; 0
704 ----
705 MachineBasicBlock *TBB = nullptr, *FBB = nullptr; 0
706 SmallVector Cond; 0
707 MachineBasicBlock *EHPadLayoutPred = MBB.getPrevNode(); 0
708 ----
709 MachineBasicBlock *Cont = &MBB; 0
710 while (Cont->isEHPad()) { 0
711 MachineInstr *Try = EHPadToTry[Cont]; 0
712 MachineInstr *EndTry = BeginToEnd[Try]; 0
713 // We started from an EH pad, so the end marker cannot be a delegate ----
714 assert(EndTry->getOpcode() != WebAssembly::DELEGATE); 0
715 Cont = EndTry->getParent(); 0
716 } ----
717 ----
718 bool Analyzable = !TII.analyzeBranch(*EHPadLayoutPred, TBB, FBB, Cond); 0
719 // This condition means either ----
720 // 1. This BB ends with a single unconditional branch whose destinaion is ----
721 // Cont. ----
722 // 2. This BB ends with a conditional branch followed by an unconditional ----
723 // branch, and the unconditional branch's destination is Cont. ----
724 // In both cases, we want to remove the last (= unconditional) branch. ----
725 if (Analyzable && ((Cond.empty() && TBB && TBB == Cont) || 0
726 (!Cond.empty() && FBB && FBB == Cont))) { 0
727 bool ErasedUncondBr = false; 0
728 (void)ErasedUncondBr; ----
729 for (auto I = EHPadLayoutPred->end(), E = EHPadLayoutPred->begin(); 0
730 I != E; --I) { 0
731 auto PrevI = std::prev(I); 0
732 if (PrevI->isTerminator()) { 0
733 assert(PrevI->getOpcode() == WebAssembly::BR); 0
734 PrevI->eraseFromParent(); 0
735 ErasedUncondBr = true; 0
736 break; 0
737 } ----
738 } ----
739 assert(ErasedUncondBr && "Unconditional branch not erased!"); 0
740 } ----
741 } 0
742 ----
743 // When there are block / end_block markers that overlap with try / end_try ----
744 // markers, and the block and try markers' return types are the same, the ----
745 // block /end_block markers are not necessary, because try / end_try markers ----
746 // also can serve as boundaries for branches. ----
747 // block <- Not necessary ----
748 // try ----
749 // ... ----
750 // catch ----
751 // ... ----
752 // end ----
753 // end <- Not necessary ----
754 SmallVector ToDelete; 0
755 for (auto &MBB : MF) { 0
756 for (auto &MI : MBB) { 0
757 if (MI.getOpcode() != WebAssembly::TRY) 0
758 continue; 0
759 MachineInstr *Try = &MI, *EndTry = BeginToEnd[Try]; 0
760 if (EndTry->getOpcode() == WebAssembly::DELEGATE) 0
761 continue; 0
762 ----
763 MachineBasicBlock *TryBB = Try->getParent(); 0
764 MachineBasicBlock *Cont = EndTry->getParent(); 0
765 int64_t RetType = Try->getOperand(0).getImm(); 0
766 for (auto B = Try->getIterator(), E = std::next(EndTry->getIterator()); 0
767 B != TryBB->begin() && E != Cont->end() && 0
768 std::prev(B)->getOpcode() == WebAssembly::BLOCK && 0
769 E->getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_BLOCK && 0
770 std::prev(B)->getOperand(0).getImm() == RetType; 0
771 --B, ++E) { 0
772 ToDelete.push_back(&*std::prev(B)); 0
773 ToDelete.push_back(&*E); 0
774 } ----
775 } ----
776 } ----
777 for (auto *MI : ToDelete) { 0
778 if (MI->getOpcode() == WebAssembly::BLOCK) 0
779 unregisterScope(MI); 0
780 MI->eraseFromParent(); 0
781 } ----
782 } 0
783 ----
784 // When MBB is split into MBB and Split, we should unstackify defs in MBB that ----
785 // have their uses in Split. ----
786 static void unstackifyVRegsUsedInSplitBB(MachineBasicBlock &MBB, 0
787 MachineBasicBlock &Split) { ----
788 MachineFunction &MF = *MBB.getParent(); 0
789 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
790 auto &MFI = *MF.getInfo(); 0
791 auto &MRI = MF.getRegInfo(); 0
792 ----
793 for (auto &MI : Split) { 0
794 for (auto &MO : MI.explicit_uses()) { 0
795 if (!MO.isReg() || MO.getReg().isPhysical()) 0
796 continue; 0
797 if (MachineInstr *Def = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(MO.getReg())) 0
798 if (Def->getParent() == &MBB) 0
799 MFI.unstackifyVReg(MO.getReg()); 0
800 } ----
801 } ----
802 ----
803 // In RegStackify, when a register definition is used multiple times, ----
804 // Reg = INST ... ----
805 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
806 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
807 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
808 // ----
809 // we introduce a TEE, which has the following form: ----
810 // DefReg = INST ... ----
811 // TeeReg, Reg = TEE_... DefReg ----
812 // INST ..., TeeReg, ... ----
813 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
814 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
815 // with DefReg and TeeReg stackified but Reg not stackified. ----
816 // ----
817 // But the invariant that TeeReg should be stackified can be violated while we ----
818 // unstackify registers in the split BB above. In this case, we convert TEEs ----
819 // into two COPYs. This COPY will be eventually eliminated in ExplicitLocals. ----
820 // DefReg = INST ... ----
821 // TeeReg = COPY DefReg ----
822 // Reg = COPY DefReg ----
823 // INST ..., TeeReg, ... ----
824 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
825 // INST ..., Reg, ... ----
826 for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::make_early_inc_range(MBB)) { 0
827 if (!WebAssembly::isTee(MI.getOpcode())) 0
828 continue; 0
829 Register TeeReg = MI.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
830 Register Reg = MI.getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
831 Register DefReg = MI.getOperand(2).getReg(); 0
832 if (!MFI.isVRegStackified(TeeReg)) { 0
833 // Now we are not using TEE anymore, so unstackify DefReg too ----
834 MFI.unstackifyVReg(DefReg); 0
835 unsigned CopyOpc = ----
836 WebAssembly::getCopyOpcodeForRegClass(MRI.getRegClass(DefReg)); 0
837 BuildMI(MBB, &MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), TII.get(CopyOpc), TeeReg) 0
838 .addReg(DefReg); 0
839 BuildMI(MBB, &MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), TII.get(CopyOpc), Reg).addReg(DefReg); 0
840 MI.eraseFromParent(); 0
841 } ----
842 } ----
843 } 0
844 ----
845 // Wrap the given range of instruction with try-delegate. RangeBegin and ----
846 // RangeEnd are inclusive. ----
847 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::addTryDelegate(MachineInstr *RangeBegin, 0
848 MachineInstr *RangeEnd, ----
849 MachineBasicBlock *DelegateDest) { ----
850 auto *BeginBB = RangeBegin->getParent(); 0
851 auto *EndBB = RangeEnd->getParent(); 0
852 MachineFunction &MF = *BeginBB->getParent(); 0
853 const auto &MFI = *MF.getInfo(); 0
854 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
855 ----
856 // Local expression tree before the first call of this range should go ----
857 // after the nested TRY. ----
858 SmallPtrSet AfterSet; 0
859 AfterSet.insert(RangeBegin); 0
860 for (auto I = MachineBasicBlock::iterator(RangeBegin), E = BeginBB->begin(); 0
861 I != E; --I) { 0
862 if (std::prev(I)->isDebugInstr() || std::prev(I)->isPosition()) 0
863 continue; 0
864 if (WebAssembly::isChild(*std::prev(I), MFI)) 0
865 AfterSet.insert(&*std::prev(I)); 0
866 else ----
867 break; 0
868 } ----
869 ----
870 // Create the nested try instruction. ----
871 auto TryPos = getLatestInsertPos( 0
872 BeginBB, SmallPtrSet(), AfterSet); 0
873 MachineInstr *Try = BuildMI(*BeginBB, TryPos, RangeBegin->getDebugLoc(), 0
874 TII.get(WebAssembly::TRY)) ----
875 .addImm(int64_t(WebAssembly::BlockType::Void)); 0
876 ----
877 // Create a BB to insert the 'delegate' instruction. ----
878 MachineBasicBlock *DelegateBB = MF.CreateMachineBasicBlock(); 0
879 // If the destination of 'delegate' is not the caller, adds the destination to ----
880 // the BB's successors. ----
881 if (DelegateDest != FakeCallerBB) 0
882 DelegateBB->addSuccessor(DelegateDest); 0
883 ----
884 auto SplitPos = std::next(RangeEnd->getIterator()); 0
885 if (SplitPos == EndBB->end()) { 0
886 // If the range's end instruction is at the end of the BB, insert the new ----
887 // delegate BB after the current BB. ----
888 MF.insert(std::next(EndBB->getIterator()), DelegateBB); 0
889 EndBB->addSuccessor(DelegateBB); 0
890 ----
891 } else { ----
892 // When the split pos is in the middle of a BB, we split the BB into two and ----
893 // put the 'delegate' BB in between. We normally create a split BB and make ----
894 // it a successor of the original BB (PostSplit == true), but in case the BB ----
895 // is an EH pad and the split pos is before 'catch', we should preserve the ----
896 // BB's property, including that it is an EH pad, in the later part of the ----
897 // BB, where 'catch' is. In this case we set PostSplit to false. ----
898 bool PostSplit = true; 0
899 if (EndBB->isEHPad()) { 0
900 for (auto I = MachineBasicBlock::iterator(SplitPos), E = EndBB->end(); 0
901 I != E; ++I) { 0
902 if (WebAssembly::isCatch(I->getOpcode())) { 0
903 PostSplit = false; 0
904 break; 0
905 } ----
906 } ----
907 } ----
908 ----
909 MachineBasicBlock *PreBB = nullptr, *PostBB = nullptr; 0
910 if (PostSplit) { 0
911 // If the range's end instruction is in the middle of the BB, we split the ----
912 // BB into two and insert the delegate BB in between. ----
913 // - Before: ----
914 // bb: ----
915 // range_end ----
916 // other_insts ----
917 // ----
918 // - After: ----
919 // pre_bb: (previous 'bb') ----
920 // range_end ----
921 // delegate_bb: (new) ----
922 // delegate ----
923 // post_bb: (new) ----
924 // other_insts ----
925 PreBB = EndBB; 0
926 PostBB = MF.CreateMachineBasicBlock(); 0
927 MF.insert(std::next(PreBB->getIterator()), PostBB); 0
928 MF.insert(std::next(PreBB->getIterator()), DelegateBB); 0
929 PostBB->splice(PostBB->end(), PreBB, SplitPos, PreBB->end()); 0
930 PostBB->transferSuccessors(PreBB); 0
931 } else { ----
932 // - Before: ----
933 // ehpad: ----
934 // range_end ----
935 // catch ----
936 // ... ----
937 // ----
938 // - After: ----
939 // pre_bb: (new) ----
940 // range_end ----
941 // delegate_bb: (new) ----
942 // delegate ----
943 // post_bb: (previous 'ehpad') ----
944 // catch ----
945 // ... ----
946 assert(EndBB->isEHPad()); 0
947 PreBB = MF.CreateMachineBasicBlock(); 0
948 PostBB = EndBB; 0
949 MF.insert(PostBB->getIterator(), PreBB); 0
950 MF.insert(PostBB->getIterator(), DelegateBB); 0
951 PreBB->splice(PreBB->end(), PostBB, PostBB->begin(), SplitPos); 0
952 // We don't need to transfer predecessors of the EH pad to 'PreBB', ----
953 // because an EH pad's predecessors are all through unwind edges and they ----
954 // should still unwind to the EH pad, not PreBB. ----
955 } ----
956 unstackifyVRegsUsedInSplitBB(*PreBB, *PostBB); 0
957 PreBB->addSuccessor(DelegateBB); 0
958 PreBB->addSuccessor(PostBB); 0
959 } ----
960 ----
961 // Add 'delegate' instruction in the delegate BB created above. ----
962 MachineInstr *Delegate = BuildMI(DelegateBB, RangeEnd->getDebugLoc(), 0
963 TII.get(WebAssembly::DELEGATE)) ----
964 .addMBB(DelegateDest); 0
965 registerTryScope(Try, Delegate, nullptr); 0
966 } 0
967 ----
968 bool WebAssemblyCFGStackify::fixCallUnwindMismatches(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
969 // Linearizing the control flow by placing TRY / END_TRY markers can create ----
970 // mismatches in unwind destinations for throwing instructions, such as calls. ----
971 // ----
972 // We use the 'delegate' instruction to fix the unwind mismatches. 'delegate' ----
973 // instruction delegates an exception to an outer 'catch'. It can target not ----
974 // only 'catch' but all block-like structures including another 'delegate', ----
975 // but with slightly different semantics than branches. When it targets a ----
976 // 'catch', it will delegate the exception to that catch. It is being ----
977 // discussed how to define the semantics when 'delegate''s target is a non-try ----
978 // block: it will either be a validation failure or it will target the next ----
979 // outer try-catch. But anyway our LLVM backend currently does not generate ----
980 // such code. The example below illustrates where the 'delegate' instruction ----
981 // in the middle will delegate the exception to, depending on the value of N. ----
982 // try ----
983 // try ----
984 // block ----
985 // try ----
986 // try ----
987 // call @foo ----
988 // delegate N ;; Where will this delegate to? ----
989 // catch ;; N == 0 ----
990 // end ----
991 // end ;; N == 1 (invalid; will not be generated) ----
992 // delegate ;; N == 2 ----
993 // catch ;; N == 3 ----
994 // end ----
995 // ;; N == 4 (to caller) ----
996 ----
997 // 1. When an instruction may throw, but the EH pad it will unwind to can be ----
998 // different from the original CFG. ----
999 // ----
1000 // Example: we have the following CFG: ----
1001 // bb0: ----
1002 // call @foo ; if it throws, unwind to bb2 ----
1003 // bb1: ----
1004 // call @bar ; if it throws, unwind to bb3 ----
1005 // bb2 (ehpad): ----
1006 // catch ----
1007 // ... ----
1008 // bb3 (ehpad) ----
1009 // catch ----
1010 // ... ----
1011 // ----
1012 // And the CFG is sorted in this order. Then after placing TRY markers, it ----
1013 // will look like: (BB markers are omitted) ----
1014 // try ----
1015 // try ----
1016 // call @foo ----
1017 // call @bar ;; if it throws, unwind to bb3 ----
1018 // catch ;; ehpad (bb2) ----
1019 // ... ----
1020 // end_try ----
1021 // catch ;; ehpad (bb3) ----
1022 // ... ----
1023 // end_try ----
1024 // ----
1025 // Now if bar() throws, it is going to end up ip in bb2, not bb3, where it ----
1026 // is supposed to end up. We solve this problem by wrapping the mismatching ----
1027 // call with an inner try-delegate that rethrows the exception to the right ----
1028 // 'catch'. ----
1029 // ----
1030 // try ----
1031 // try ----
1032 // call @foo ----
1033 // try ;; (new) ----
1034 // call @bar ----
1035 // delegate 1 (bb3) ;; (new) ----
1036 // catch ;; ehpad (bb2) ----
1037 // ... ----
1038 // end_try ----
1039 // catch ;; ehpad (bb3) ----
1040 // ... ----
1041 // end_try ----
1042 // ----
1043 // --- ----
1044 // 2. The same as 1, but in this case an instruction unwinds to a caller ----
1045 // function and not another EH pad. ----
1046 // ----
1047 // Example: we have the following CFG: ----
1048 // bb0: ----
1049 // call @foo ; if it throws, unwind to bb2 ----
1050 // bb1: ----
1051 // call @bar ; if it throws, unwind to caller ----
1052 // bb2 (ehpad): ----
1053 // catch ----
1054 // ... ----
1055 // ----
1056 // And the CFG is sorted in this order. Then after placing TRY markers, it ----
1057 // will look like: ----
1058 // try ----
1059 // call @foo ----
1060 // call @bar ;; if it throws, unwind to caller ----
1061 // catch ;; ehpad (bb2) ----
1062 // ... ----
1063 // end_try ----
1064 // ----
1065 // Now if bar() throws, it is going to end up ip in bb2, when it is supposed ----
1066 // throw up to the caller. We solve this problem in the same way, but in this ----
1067 // case 'delegate's immediate argument is the number of block depths + 1, ----
1068 // which means it rethrows to the caller. ----
1069 // try ----
1070 // call @foo ----
1071 // try ;; (new) ----
1072 // call @bar ----
1073 // delegate 1 (caller) ;; (new) ----
1074 // catch ;; ehpad (bb2) ----
1075 // ... ----
1076 // end_try ----
1077 // ----
1078 // Before rewriteDepthImmediates, delegate's argument is a BB. In case of the ----
1079 // caller, it will take a fake BB generated by getFakeCallerBlock(), which ----
1080 // will be converted to a correct immediate argument later. ----
1081 // ----
1082 // In case there are multiple calls in a BB that may throw to the caller, they ----
1083 // can be wrapped together in one nested try-delegate scope. (In 1, this ----
1084 // couldn't happen, because may-throwing instruction there had an unwind ----
1085 // destination, i.e., it was an invoke before, and there could be only one ----
1086 // invoke within a BB.) ----
1087 ----
1088 SmallVector EHPadStack; 0
1089 // Range of intructions to be wrapped in a new nested try/catch. A range ----
1090 // exists in a single BB and does not span multiple BBs. ----
1091 using TryRange = std::pair; ----
1092 // In original CFG, ----
1093 DenseMap> UnwindDestToTryRanges; 0
1094 ----
1095 // Gather possibly throwing calls (i.e., previously invokes) whose current ----
1096 // unwind destination is not the same as the original CFG. (Case 1) ----
1097 ----
1098 for (auto &MBB : reverse(MF)) { 0
1099 bool SeenThrowableInstInBB = false; 0
1100 for (auto &MI : reverse(MBB)) { 0
1101 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::TRY) 0
1102 EHPadStack.pop_back(); 0
1103 else if (WebAssembly::isCatch(MI.getOpcode())) 0
1104 EHPadStack.push_back(MI.getParent()); 0
1105 ----
1106 // In this loop we only gather calls that have an EH pad to unwind. So ----
1107 // there will be at most 1 such call (= invoke) in a BB, so after we've ----
1108 // seen one, we can skip the rest of BB. Also if MBB has no EH pad ----
1109 // successor or MI does not throw, this is not an invoke. ----
1110 if (SeenThrowableInstInBB || !MBB.hasEHPadSuccessor() || 0
1111 !WebAssembly::mayThrow(MI)) 0
1112 continue; 0
1113 SeenThrowableInstInBB = true; 0
1114 ----
1115 // If the EH pad on the stack top is where this instruction should unwind ----
1116 // next, we're good. ----
1117 MachineBasicBlock *UnwindDest = getFakeCallerBlock(MF); 0
1118 for (auto *Succ : MBB.successors()) { 0
1119 // Even though semantically a BB can have multiple successors in case an ----
1120 // exception is not caught by a catchpad, in our backend implementation ----
1121 // it is guaranteed that a BB can have at most one EH pad successor. For ----
1122 // details, refer to comments in findWasmUnwindDestinations function in ----
1123 // SelectionDAGBuilder.cpp. ----
1124 if (Succ->isEHPad()) { 0
1125 UnwindDest = Succ; 0
1126 break; 0
1127 } ----
1128 } ----
1129 if (EHPadStack.back() == UnwindDest) 0
1130 continue; 0
1131 ----
1132 // Include EH_LABELs in the range before and afer the invoke ----
1133 MachineInstr *RangeBegin = &MI, *RangeEnd = &MI; 0
1134 if (RangeBegin->getIterator() != MBB.begin() && 0
1135 std::prev(RangeBegin->getIterator())->isEHLabel()) 0
1136 RangeBegin = &*std::prev(RangeBegin->getIterator()); 0
1137 if (std::next(RangeEnd->getIterator()) != MBB.end() && 0
1138 std::next(RangeEnd->getIterator())->isEHLabel()) 0
1139 RangeEnd = &*std::next(RangeEnd->getIterator()); 0
1140 ----
1141 // If not, record the range. ----
1142 UnwindDestToTryRanges[UnwindDest].push_back( 0
1143 TryRange(RangeBegin, RangeEnd)); ----
1144 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Call unwind mismatch: MBB = " << MBB.getName() 0
1145 << "\nCall = " << MI ----
1146 << "\nOriginal dest = " << UnwindDest->getName() ----
1147 << " Current dest = " << EHPadStack.back()->getName() ----
1148 << "\n\n"); ----
1149 } ----
1150 } ----
1151 ----
1152 assert(EHPadStack.empty()); 0
1153 ----
1154 // Gather possibly throwing calls that are supposed to unwind up to the caller ----
1155 // if they throw, but currently unwind to an incorrect destination. Unlike the ----
1156 // loop above, there can be multiple calls within a BB that unwind to the ----
1157 // caller, which we should group together in a range. (Case 2) ----
1158 ----
1159 MachineInstr *RangeBegin = nullptr, *RangeEnd = nullptr; // inclusive 0
1160 ----
1161 // Record the range. ----
1162 auto RecordCallerMismatchRange = [&](const MachineBasicBlock *CurrentDest) { 0
1163 UnwindDestToTryRanges[getFakeCallerBlock(MF)].push_back( 0
1164 TryRange(RangeBegin, RangeEnd)); 0
1165 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Call unwind mismatch: MBB = " 0
1166 << RangeBegin->getParent()->getName() ----
1167 << "\nRange begin = " << *RangeBegin ----
1168 << "Range end = " << *RangeEnd ----
1169 << "\nOriginal dest = caller Current dest = " ----
1170 << CurrentDest->getName() << "\n\n"); ----
1171 RangeBegin = RangeEnd = nullptr; // Reset range pointers 0
1172 }; 0
1173 ----
1174 for (auto &MBB : reverse(MF)) { 0
1175 bool SeenThrowableInstInBB = false; 0
1176 for (auto &MI : reverse(MBB)) { 0
1177 bool MayThrow = WebAssembly::mayThrow(MI); 0
1178 ----
1179 // If MBB has an EH pad successor and this is the last instruction that ----
1180 // may throw, this instruction unwinds to the EH pad and not to the ----
1181 // caller. ----
1182 if (MBB.hasEHPadSuccessor() && MayThrow && !SeenThrowableInstInBB) 0
1183 SeenThrowableInstInBB = true; 0
1184 ----
1185 // We wrap up the current range when we see a marker even if we haven't ----
1186 // finished a BB. ----
1187 else if (RangeEnd && WebAssembly::isMarker(MI.getOpcode())) 0
1188 RecordCallerMismatchRange(EHPadStack.back()); 0
1189 ----
1190 // If EHPadStack is empty, that means it correctly unwinds to the caller ----
1191 // if it throws, so we're good. If MI does not throw, we're good too. ----
1192 else if (EHPadStack.empty() || !MayThrow) { 0
1193 } ----
1194 ----
1195 // We found an instruction that unwinds to the caller but currently has an ----
1196 // incorrect unwind destination. Create a new range or increment the ----
1197 // currently existing range. ----
1198 else { ----
1199 if (!RangeEnd) 0
1200 RangeBegin = RangeEnd = &MI; 0
1201 else ----
1202 RangeBegin = &MI; 0
1203 } ----
1204 ----
1205 // Update EHPadStack. ----
1206 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::TRY) 0
1207 EHPadStack.pop_back(); 0
1208 else if (WebAssembly::isCatch(MI.getOpcode())) 0
1209 EHPadStack.push_back(MI.getParent()); 0
1210 } ----
1211 ----
1212 if (RangeEnd) 0
1213 RecordCallerMismatchRange(EHPadStack.back()); 0
1214 } ----
1215 ----
1216 assert(EHPadStack.empty()); 0
1217 ----
1218 // We don't have any unwind destination mismatches to resolve. ----
1219 if (UnwindDestToTryRanges.empty()) 0
1220 return false; 0
1221 ----
1222 // Now we fix the mismatches by wrapping calls with inner try-delegates. ----
1223 for (auto &P : UnwindDestToTryRanges) { 0
1224 NumCallUnwindMismatches += P.second.size(); 0
1225 MachineBasicBlock *UnwindDest = P.first; 0
1226 auto &TryRanges = P.second; 0
1227 ----
1228 for (auto Range : TryRanges) { 0
1229 MachineInstr *RangeBegin = nullptr, *RangeEnd = nullptr; 0
1230 std::tie(RangeBegin, RangeEnd) = Range; 0
1231 auto *MBB = RangeBegin->getParent(); 0
1232 ----
1233 // If this BB has an EH pad successor, i.e., ends with an 'invoke', now we ----
1234 // are going to wrap the invoke with try-delegate, making the 'delegate' ----
1235 // BB the new successor instead, so remove the EH pad succesor here. The ----
1236 // BB may not have an EH pad successor if calls in this BB throw to the ----
1237 // caller. ----
1238 MachineBasicBlock *EHPad = nullptr; 0
1239 for (auto *Succ : MBB->successors()) { 0
1240 if (Succ->isEHPad()) { 0
1241 EHPad = Succ; 0
1242 break; 0
1243 } ----
1244 } ----
1245 if (EHPad) 0
1246 MBB->removeSuccessor(EHPad); 0
1247 ----
1248 addTryDelegate(RangeBegin, RangeEnd, UnwindDest); 0
1249 } ----
1250 } ----
1251 ----
1252 return true; 0
1253 } 0
1254 ----
1255 bool WebAssemblyCFGStackify::fixCatchUnwindMismatches(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1256 // There is another kind of unwind destination mismatches besides call unwind ----
1257 // mismatches, which we will call "catch unwind mismatches". See this example ----
1258 // after the marker placement: ----
1259 // try ----
1260 // try ----
1261 // call @foo ----
1262 // catch __cpp_exception ;; ehpad A (next unwind dest: caller) ----
1263 // ... ----
1264 // end_try ----
1265 // catch_all ;; ehpad B ----
1266 // ... ----
1267 // end_try ----
1268 // ----
1269 // 'call @foo's unwind destination is the ehpad A. But suppose 'call @foo' ----
1270 // throws a foreign exception that is not caught by ehpad A, and its next ----
1271 // destination should be the caller. But after control flow linearization, ----
1272 // another EH pad can be placed in between (e.g. ehpad B here), making the ----
1273 // next unwind destination incorrect. In this case, the foreign exception ----
1274 // will instead go to ehpad B and will be caught there instead. In this ----
1275 // example the correct next unwind destination is the caller, but it can be ----
1276 // another outer catch in other cases. ----
1277 // ----
1278 // There is no specific 'call' or 'throw' instruction to wrap with a ----
1279 // try-delegate, so we wrap the whole try-catch-end with a try-delegate and ----
1280 // make it rethrow to the right destination, as in the example below: ----
1281 // try ----
1282 // try ;; (new) ----
1283 // try ----
1284 // call @foo ----
1285 // catch __cpp_exception ;; ehpad A (next unwind dest: caller) ----
1286 // ... ----
1287 // end_try ----
1288 // delegate 1 (caller) ;; (new) ----
1289 // catch_all ;; ehpad B ----
1290 // ... ----
1291 // end_try ----
1292 ----
1293 const auto *EHInfo = MF.getWasmEHFuncInfo(); 0
1294 assert(EHInfo); 0
1295 SmallVector EHPadStack; 0
1296 // For EH pads that have catch unwind mismatches, a map of ----
1297 // correct unwind destination>. ----
1298 DenseMap EHPadToUnwindDest; 0
1299 ----
1300 for (auto &MBB : reverse(MF)) { 0
1301 for (auto &MI : reverse(MBB)) { 0
1302 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::TRY) 0
1303 EHPadStack.pop_back(); 0
1304 else if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::DELEGATE) 0
1305 EHPadStack.push_back(&MBB); 0
1306 else if (WebAssembly::isCatch(MI.getOpcode())) { 0
1307 auto *EHPad = &MBB; 0
1308 ----
1309 // catch_all always catches an exception, so we don't need to do ----
1310 // anything ----
1311 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::CATCH_ALL) { 0
1312 } ----
1313 ----
1314 // This can happen when the unwind dest was removed during the ----
1315 // optimization, e.g. because it was unreachable. ----
1316 else if (EHPadStack.empty() && EHInfo->hasUnwindDest(EHPad)) { 0
1317 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "EHPad (" << EHPad->getName() 0
1318 << "'s unwind destination does not exist anymore" ----
1319 << "\n\n"); ----
1320 } ----
1321 ----
1322 // The EHPad's next unwind destination is the caller, but we incorrectly ----
1323 // unwind to another EH pad. ----
1324 else if (!EHPadStack.empty() && !EHInfo->hasUnwindDest(EHPad)) { 0
1325 EHPadToUnwindDest[EHPad] = getFakeCallerBlock(MF); 0
1326 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() 0
1327 << "- Catch unwind mismatch:\nEHPad = " << EHPad->getName() ----
1328 << " Original dest = caller Current dest = " ----
1329 << EHPadStack.back()->getName() << "\n\n"); ----
1330 } ----
1331 ----
1332 // The EHPad's next unwind destination is an EH pad, whereas we ----
1333 // incorrectly unwind to another EH pad. ----
1334 else if (!EHPadStack.empty() && EHInfo->hasUnwindDest(EHPad)) { 0
1335 auto *UnwindDest = EHInfo->getUnwindDest(EHPad); 0
1336 if (EHPadStack.back() != UnwindDest) { 0
1337 EHPadToUnwindDest[EHPad] = UnwindDest; 0
1338 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "- Catch unwind mismatch:\nEHPad = " 0
1339 << EHPad->getName() << " Original dest = " ----
1340 << UnwindDest->getName() << " Current dest = " ----
1341 << EHPadStack.back()->getName() << "\n\n"); ----
1342 } ----
1343 } ----
1344 ----
1345 EHPadStack.push_back(EHPad); 0
1346 } ----
1347 } ----
1348 } ----
1349 ----
1350 assert(EHPadStack.empty()); 0
1351 if (EHPadToUnwindDest.empty()) 0
1352 return false; 0
1353 NumCatchUnwindMismatches += EHPadToUnwindDest.size(); 0
1354 SmallPtrSet NewEndTryBBs; 0
1355 ----
1356 for (auto &P : EHPadToUnwindDest) { 0
1357 MachineBasicBlock *EHPad = P.first; 0
1358 MachineBasicBlock *UnwindDest = P.second; 0
1359 MachineInstr *Try = EHPadToTry[EHPad]; 0
1360 MachineInstr *EndTry = BeginToEnd[Try]; 0
1361 addTryDelegate(Try, EndTry, UnwindDest); 0
1362 NewEndTryBBs.insert(EndTry->getParent()); 0
1363 } ----
1364 ----
1365 // Adding a try-delegate wrapping an existing try-catch-end can make existing ----
1366 // branch destination BBs invalid. For example, ----
1367 // ----
1368 // - Before: ----
1369 // bb0: ----
1370 // block ----
1371 // br bb3 ----
1372 // bb1: ----
1373 // try ----
1374 // ... ----
1375 // bb2: (ehpad) ----
1376 // catch ----
1377 // bb3: ----
1378 // end_try ----
1379 // end_block ;; 'br bb3' targets here ----
1380 // ----
1381 // Suppose this try-catch-end has a catch unwind mismatch, so we need to wrap ----
1382 // this with a try-delegate. Then this becomes: ----
1383 // ----
1384 // - After: ----
1385 // bb0: ----
1386 // block ----
1387 // br bb3 ;; invalid destination! ----
1388 // bb1: ----
1389 // try ;; (new instruction) ----
1390 // try ----
1391 // ... ----
1392 // bb2: (ehpad) ----
1393 // catch ----
1394 // bb3: ----
1395 // end_try ;; 'br bb3' still incorrectly targets here! ----
1396 // delegate_bb: ;; (new BB) ----
1397 // delegate ;; (new instruction) ----
1398 // split_bb: ;; (new BB) ----
1399 // end_block ----
1400 // ----
1401 // Now 'br bb3' incorrectly branches to an inner scope. ----
1402 // ----
1403 // As we can see in this case, when branches target a BB that has both ----
1404 // 'end_try' and 'end_block' and the BB is split to insert a 'delegate', we ----
1405 // have to remap existing branch destinations so that they target not the ----
1406 // 'end_try' BB but the new 'end_block' BB. There can be multiple 'delegate's ----
1407 // in between, so we try to find the next BB with 'end_block' instruction. In ----
1408 // this example, the 'br bb3' instruction should be remapped to 'br split_bb'. ----
1409 for (auto &MBB : MF) { 0
1410 for (auto &MI : MBB) { 0
1411 if (MI.isTerminator()) { 0
1412 for (auto &MO : MI.operands()) { 0
1413 if (MO.isMBB() && NewEndTryBBs.count(MO.getMBB())) { 0
1414 auto *BrDest = MO.getMBB(); 0
1415 bool FoundEndBlock = false; 0
1416 for (; std::next(BrDest->getIterator()) != MF.end(); 0
1417 BrDest = BrDest->getNextNode()) { 0
1418 for (const auto &MI : *BrDest) { 0
1419 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_BLOCK) { 0
1420 FoundEndBlock = true; 0
1421 break; 0
1422 } ----
1423 } ----
1424 if (FoundEndBlock) 0
1425 break; 0
1426 } ----
1427 assert(FoundEndBlock); 0
1428 MO.setMBB(BrDest); 0
1429 } ----
1430 } ----
1431 } ----
1432 } ----
1433 } ----
1434 ----
1435 return true; 0
1436 } 0
1437 ----
1438 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::recalculateScopeTops(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1439 // Renumber BBs and recalculate ScopeTop info because new BBs might have been ----
1440 // created and inserted during fixing unwind mismatches. ----
1441 MF.RenumberBlocks(); 0
1442 ScopeTops.clear(); 0
1443 ScopeTops.resize(MF.getNumBlockIDs()); 0
1444 for (auto &MBB : reverse(MF)) { 0
1445 for (auto &MI : reverse(MBB)) { 0
1446 if (ScopeTops[MBB.getNumber()]) 0
1447 break; 0
1448 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
1449 case WebAssembly::END_BLOCK: 0
1450 case WebAssembly::END_LOOP: ----
1451 case WebAssembly::END_TRY: ----
1452 case WebAssembly::DELEGATE: ----
1453 updateScopeTops(EndToBegin[&MI]->getParent(), &MBB); 0
1454 break; 0
1455 case WebAssembly::CATCH: 0
1456 case WebAssembly::CATCH_ALL: ----
1457 updateScopeTops(EHPadToTry[&MBB]->getParent(), &MBB); 0
1458 break; 0
1459 } ----
1460 } ----
1461 } ----
1462 } 0
1463 ----
1464 /// In normal assembly languages, when the end of a function is unreachable, ----
1465 /// because the function ends in an infinite loop or a noreturn call or similar, ----
1466 /// it isn't necessary to worry about the function return type at the end of ----
1467 /// the function, because it's never reached. However, in WebAssembly, blocks ----
1468 /// that end at the function end need to have a return type signature that ----
1469 /// matches the function signature, even though it's unreachable. This function ----
1470 /// checks for such cases and fixes up the signatures. ----
1471 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::fixEndsAtEndOfFunction(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1472 const auto &MFI = *MF.getInfo(); 0
1473 ----
1474 if (MFI.getResults().empty()) 0
1475 return; 0
1476 ----
1477 // MCInstLower will add the proper types to multivalue signatures based on the ----
1478 // function return type ----
1479 WebAssembly::BlockType RetType = ----
1480 MFI.getResults().size() > 1 0
1481 ? WebAssembly::BlockType::Multivalue 0
1482 : WebAssembly::BlockType( ----
1483 WebAssembly::toValType(MFI.getResults().front())); 0
1484 ----
1485 SmallVector Worklist; 0
1486 Worklist.push_back(MF.rbegin()->rbegin()); 0
1487 ----
1488 auto Process = [&](MachineBasicBlock::reverse_iterator It) { 0
1489 auto *MBB = It->getParent(); 0
1490 while (It != MBB->rend()) { 0
1491 MachineInstr &MI = *It++; 0
1492 if (MI.isPosition() || MI.isDebugInstr()) 0
1493 continue; 0
1494 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
1495 case WebAssembly::END_TRY: { 0
1496 // If a 'try''s return type is fixed, both its try body and catch body ----
1497 // should satisfy the return type, so we need to search 'end' ----
1498 // instructions before its corresponding 'catch' too. ----
1499 auto *EHPad = TryToEHPad.lookup(EndToBegin[&MI]); 0
1500 assert(EHPad); 0
1501 auto NextIt = ----
1502 std::next(WebAssembly::findCatch(EHPad)->getReverseIterator()); 0
1503 if (NextIt != EHPad->rend()) 0
1504 Worklist.push_back(NextIt); 0
1505 [[fallthrough]]; ----
1506 } ----
1507 case WebAssembly::END_BLOCK: 0
1508 case WebAssembly::END_LOOP: ----
1509 case WebAssembly::DELEGATE: ----
1510 EndToBegin[&MI]->getOperand(0).setImm(int32_t(RetType)); 0
1511 continue; 0
1512 default: 0
1513 // Something other than an `end`. We're done for this BB. ----
1514 return; 0
1515 } 0
1516 } ----
1517 // We've reached the beginning of a BB. Continue the search in the previous ----
1518 // BB. ----
1519 Worklist.push_back(MBB->getPrevNode()->rbegin()); 0
1520 }; 0
1521 ----
1522 while (!Worklist.empty()) 0
1523 Process(Worklist.pop_back_val()); 0
1524 } 0
1525 ----
1526 // WebAssembly functions end with an end instruction, as if the function body ----
1527 // were a block. ----
1528 static void appendEndToFunction(MachineFunction &MF, 0
1529 const WebAssemblyInstrInfo &TII) { ----
1530 BuildMI(MF.back(), MF.back().end(), 0
1531 MF.back().findPrevDebugLoc(MF.back().end()), 0
1532 TII.get(WebAssembly::END_FUNCTION)); ----
1533 } 0

1535 /// Insert LOOP/TRY/BLOCK markers at appropriate places. ----
1536 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::placeMarkers(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1537 // We allocate one more than the number of blocks in the function to ----
1538 // accommodate for the possible fake block we may insert at the end. ----
1539 ScopeTops.resize(MF.getNumBlockIDs() + 1); 0
1540 // Place the LOOP for MBB if MBB is the header of a loop. ----
1541 for (auto &MBB : MF) 0
1542 placeLoopMarker(MBB); 0
1543 ----
1544 const MCAsmInfo *MCAI = MF.getTarget().getMCAsmInfo(); 0
1545 for (auto &MBB : MF) { 0
1546 if (MBB.isEHPad()) { 0
1547 // Place the TRY for MBB if MBB is the EH pad of an exception. ----
1548 if (MCAI->getExceptionHandlingType() == ExceptionHandling::Wasm && 0
1549 MF.getFunction().hasPersonalityFn()) 0
1550 placeTryMarker(MBB); 0
1551 } else { ----
1552 // Place the BLOCK for MBB if MBB is branched to from above. ----
1553 placeBlockMarker(MBB); 0
1554 } ----
1555 } ----
1556 // Fix mismatches in unwind destinations induced by linearizing the code. ----
1557 if (MCAI->getExceptionHandlingType() == ExceptionHandling::Wasm && 0
1558 MF.getFunction().hasPersonalityFn()) { 0
1559 bool Changed = fixCallUnwindMismatches(MF); 0
1560 Changed |= fixCatchUnwindMismatches(MF); 0
1561 if (Changed) 0
1562 recalculateScopeTops(MF); 0
1563 } ----
1564 } 0

1566 unsigned WebAssemblyCFGStackify::getBranchDepth( 0
1567 const SmallVectorImpl &Stack, const MachineBasicBlock *MBB) { ----
1568 unsigned Depth = 0; 0
1569 for (auto X : reverse(Stack)) { 0
1570 if (X.first == MBB) 0
1571 break; 0
1572 ++Depth; 0
1573 } ----
1574 assert(Depth < Stack.size() && "Branch destination should be in scope"); 0
1575 return Depth; 0
1576 } ----
1577 ----
1578 unsigned WebAssemblyCFGStackify::getDelegateDepth( 0
1579 const SmallVectorImpl &Stack, const MachineBasicBlock *MBB) { ----
1580 if (MBB == FakeCallerBB) 0
1581 return Stack.size(); 0
1582 // Delegate's destination is either a catch or a another delegate BB. When the ----
1583 // destination is another delegate, we can compute the argument in the same ----
1584 // way as branches, because the target delegate BB only contains the single ----
1585 // delegate instruction. ----
1586 if (!MBB->isEHPad()) // Target is a delegate BB 0
1587 return getBranchDepth(Stack, MBB); 0
1588 ----
1589 // When the delegate's destination is a catch BB, we need to use its ----
1590 // corresponding try's end_try BB because Stack contains each marker's end BB. ----
1591 // Also we need to check if the end marker instruction matches, because a ----
1592 // single BB can contain multiple end markers, like this: ----
1593 // bb: ----
1594 // END_BLOCK ----
1595 // END_TRY ----
1596 // END_BLOCK ----
1597 // END_TRY ----
1598 // ... ----
1599 // ----
1600 // In case of branches getting the immediate that targets any of these is ----
1601 // fine, but delegate has to exactly target the correct try. ----
1602 unsigned Depth = 0; 0
1603 const MachineInstr *EndTry = BeginToEnd[EHPadToTry[MBB]]; 0
1604 for (auto X : reverse(Stack)) { 0
1605 if (X.first == EndTry->getParent() && X.second == EndTry) 0
1606 break; 0
1607 ++Depth; 0
1608 } ----
1609 assert(Depth < Stack.size() && "Delegate destination should be in scope"); 0
1610 return Depth; 0
1611 } ----
1612 ----
1613 unsigned WebAssemblyCFGStackify::getRethrowDepth( 0
1614 const SmallVectorImpl &Stack, ----
1615 const SmallVectorImpl &EHPadStack) { ----
1616 unsigned Depth = 0; 0
1617 // In our current implementation, rethrows always rethrow the exception caught ----
1618 // by the innermost enclosing catch. This means while traversing Stack in the ----
1619 // reverse direction, when we encounter END_TRY, we should check if the ----
1620 // END_TRY corresponds to the current innermost EH pad. For example: ----
1621 // try ----
1622 // ... ----
1623 // catch ;; (a) ----
1624 // try ----
1625 // rethrow 1 ;; (b) ----
1626 // catch ;; (c) ----
1627 // rethrow 0 ;; (d) ----
1628 // end ;; (e) ----
1629 // end ;; (f) ----
1630 // ----
1631 // When we are at 'rethrow' (d), while reversely traversing Stack the first ----
1632 // 'end' we encounter is the 'end' (e), which corresponds to the 'catch' (c). ----
1633 // And 'rethrow' (d) rethrows the exception caught by 'catch' (c), so we stop ----
1634 // there and the depth should be 0. But when we are at 'rethrow' (b), it ----
1635 // rethrows the exception caught by 'catch' (a), so when traversing Stack ----
1636 // reversely, we should skip the 'end' (e) and choose 'end' (f), which ----
1637 // corresponds to 'catch' (a). ----
1638 for (auto X : reverse(Stack)) { 0
1639 const MachineInstr *End = X.second; 0
1640 if (End->getOpcode() == WebAssembly::END_TRY) { 0
1641 auto *EHPad = TryToEHPad[EndToBegin[End]]; 0
1642 if (EHPadStack.back() == EHPad) 0
1643 break; 0
1644 } ----
1645 ++Depth; 0
1646 } ----
1647 assert(Depth < Stack.size() && "Rethrow destination should be in scope"); 0
1648 return Depth; 0
1649 } ----
1650 ----
1651 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::rewriteDepthImmediates(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1652 // Now rewrite references to basic blocks to be depth immediates. ----
1653 SmallVector Stack; 0
1654 SmallVector EHPadStack; 0
1655 for (auto &MBB : reverse(MF)) { 0
1656 for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::reverse(MBB)) { 0
1657 switch (MI.getOpcode()) { 0
1658 case WebAssembly::BLOCK: 0
1659 case WebAssembly::TRY: ----
1660 assert(ScopeTops[Stack.back().first->getNumber()]->getNumber() <= 0
1661 MBB.getNumber() && ----
1662 "Block/try marker should be balanced"); ----
1663 Stack.pop_back(); 0
1664 break; 0
1665 ----
1666 case WebAssembly::LOOP: 0
1667 assert(Stack.back().first == &MBB && "Loop top should be balanced"); 0
1668 Stack.pop_back(); 0
1669 break; 0
1670 ----
1671 case WebAssembly::END_BLOCK: 0
1672 Stack.push_back(std::make_pair(&MBB, &MI)); 0
1673 break; 0
1674 ----
1675 case WebAssembly::END_TRY: { 0
1676 // We handle DELEGATE in the default level, because DELEGATE has ----
1677 // immediate operands to rewrite. ----
1678 Stack.push_back(std::make_pair(&MBB, &MI)); 0
1679 auto *EHPad = TryToEHPad[EndToBegin[&MI]]; 0
1680 EHPadStack.push_back(EHPad); 0
1681 break; 0
1682 } ----
1683 ----
1684 case WebAssembly::END_LOOP: 0
1685 Stack.push_back(std::make_pair(EndToBegin[&MI]->getParent(), &MI)); 0
1686 break; 0
1687 ----
1688 case WebAssembly::CATCH: 0
1689 case WebAssembly::CATCH_ALL: ----
1690 EHPadStack.pop_back(); 0
1691 break; 0
1692 ----
1693 case WebAssembly::RETHROW: 0
1694 MI.getOperand(0).setImm(getRethrowDepth(Stack, EHPadStack)); 0
1695 break; 0
1696 ----
1697 default: 0
1698 if (MI.isTerminator()) { 0
1699 // Rewrite MBB operands to be depth immediates. ----
1700 SmallVector Ops(MI.operands()); 0
1701 while (MI.getNumOperands() > 0) 0
1702 MI.removeOperand(MI.getNumOperands() - 1); 0
1703 for (auto MO : Ops) { 0
1704 if (MO.isMBB()) { 0
1705 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::DELEGATE) 0
1706 MO = MachineOperand::CreateImm( 0
1707 getDelegateDepth(Stack, MO.getMBB())); 0
1708 else ----
1709 MO = MachineOperand::CreateImm( 0
1710 getBranchDepth(Stack, MO.getMBB())); 0
1711 } ----
1712 MI.addOperand(MF, MO); 0
1713 } ----
1714 } 0
1715 ----
1716 if (MI.getOpcode() == WebAssembly::DELEGATE) 0
1717 Stack.push_back(std::make_pair(&MBB, &MI)); 0
1718 break; 0
1719 } ----
1720 } ----
1721 } ----
1722 assert(Stack.empty() && "Control flow should be balanced"); 0
1723 } 0

1725 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::cleanupFunctionData(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1726 if (FakeCallerBB) 0
1727 MF.deleteMachineBasicBlock(FakeCallerBB); 0
1728 AppendixBB = FakeCallerBB = nullptr; 0
1729 } 0

1731 void WebAssemblyCFGStackify::releaseMemory() { 0
1732 ScopeTops.clear(); 0
1733 BeginToEnd.clear(); 0
1734 EndToBegin.clear(); 0
1735 TryToEHPad.clear(); 0
1736 EHPadToTry.clear(); 0
1737 } 0
1738 ----
1739 bool WebAssemblyCFGStackify::runOnMachineFunction(MachineFunction &MF) { 0
1740 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "********** CFG Stackifying **********\n" 0
1741 "********** Function: " ----
1742 << MF.getName() << '\n'); ----
1743 const MCAsmInfo *MCAI = MF.getTarget().getMCAsmInfo(); 0
1744 ----
1745 releaseMemory(); 0
1746 ----
1747 // Liveness is not tracked for VALUE_STACK physreg. ----
1748 MF.getRegInfo().invalidateLiveness(); 0
1749 ----
1750 // Place the BLOCK/LOOP/TRY markers to indicate the beginnings of scopes. ----
1751 placeMarkers(MF); 0
1752 ----
1753 // Remove unnecessary instructions possibly introduced by try/end_trys. ----
1754 if (MCAI->getExceptionHandlingType() == ExceptionHandling::Wasm && 0
1755 MF.getFunction().hasPersonalityFn()) 0
1756 removeUnnecessaryInstrs(MF); 0
1757 ----
1758 // Convert MBB operands in terminators to relative depth immediates. ----
1759 rewriteDepthImmediates(MF); 0
1760 ----
1761 // Fix up block/loop/try signatures at the end of the function to conform to ----
1762 // WebAssembly's rules. ----
1763 fixEndsAtEndOfFunction(MF); 0
1764 ----
1765 // Add an end instruction at the end of the function body. ----
1766 const auto &TII = *MF.getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
1767 if (!MF.getSubtarget() 0
1768 .getTargetTriple() 0
1769 .isOSBinFormatELF()) 0
1770 appendEndToFunction(MF, TII); 0
1771 ----
1772 cleanupFunctionData(MF); 0
1773 ----
1774 MF.getInfo()->setCFGStackified(); 0
1775 return true; 0
1776 } ----
